      <hedline>
        <hl1>In the Mideast Maelstrom, an American Lifeline</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jeffrey D Hoschander letter on Apr 5 editorial opposes any United States effort to limit Israel's right to respond to terror</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Like the overwhelming majority of Americans, I strongly support the president and the American war on terror. For this reason, I am concerned by the latest policy expression with regard to the conflict in the West Bank.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Like the overwhelming majority of Americans, I strongly support the president and the American war on terror. For this reason, I am concerned by the latest policy expression with regard to the conflict in the West Bank.</p>
        <p>In ''The President Steps In'' (editorial, April 5), you endorse the president's latest pronouncements on the Middle East. You contend that the administration is saying that ''Israel has a right to defend itself against terror . . . but not at the cost of regional chaos.''</p>
        <p>But such a message, whether it is your interpretation or indeed intended by the president, should be of great concern to all Americans.</p>
        <p>By publicly seeking to limit Israel's right to respond to terror before the international community, the United States undermines its own efforts to do so.  JEFFREY D. HOSCHANDER  Stamford, Conn., April 5, 2002</p>
      </block>
